n presided as chairman of the 1860 Republican National Convention in Chicago — the gathering that made Abraham Lincoln the Republican nominee for president. On April 14, 1865, the final day of Lincoln's life, the President personally wrote Ashmun a note admitting him to the White House: it is among the last things Lincoln ever wrote."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Father a senator; son served four congressional terms","body":"His father Eli Porter Ashmun served in the United States Senate from 1816 to 1818; George followed into federal office with four terms in the Massachusetts House delegation from 1845 to 1851. He retired from Congress fourteen years before presiding at the convention that made Lincoln's presidency possible."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Lincoln wrote to him hours before the assassination","body":"On April 14, 1865, Abraham Lincoln wrote George Ashmun a personal note admitting him to the White House: 'Allow Mr. Ashmun & friend to come in. —A Lincoln.' Lincoln was shot at Ford's Theatre that same evening; the note is among the last things the President ever wrote, and is preserved in presidential archives."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM413"},"slug":"george-ashmun-1804"},"HD4945":{"id":"HD4945","is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"former_ids":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elizabeth Hall Ashmun Morton","first_name":"Elizabeth","middle_name":"Hall","last_name":"Ashmun","married_names":["Morton"]},"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1829,"state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1916,"country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0613","mother_id":"X00230"},"notable":{"is_no